{"title_page": "Jos\u00e9 Luis Ablanedo", "text_new": "{{spanish name 2|Ablanedo|Iglesias}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2013}}\n{{Infobox football biography\n| name = Jos\u00e9 Luis Ablanedo\n| image = \n| fullname = Jos\u00e9 Luis Ablanedo Iglesias\n| birth_date = {{birth date and age|1962|8|22|df=y}}\n| birth_place = [[Mieres, Asturias|Mieres]], [[Spain]]\n| height = {{height|m=1.85}}\n| position = [[Defender (association football)#Centre-back|Centre back]]\n| currentclub = \n| clubnumber = \n| youthyears1 = | youthclubs1 = [[Sporting de Gij\u00f3n (youth)|Sporting Gij\u00f3n]]\n| years1 = 1981\u20131985 | clubs1 = [[Sporting de Gij\u00f3n B|Sporting Gij\u00f3n B]] | caps1 = 98 | goals1 = 2\n| years2 = 1984\u20131994 | clubs2 = [[Sporting de Gij\u00f3n|Sporting Gij\u00f3n]] | caps2 = 174 | goals2 = 7\n| years3 = 1991\u20131992 | clubs3 = \u2192 [[RCD Espanyol|Espa\u00f1ol]] (loan) | caps3 = 8 | goals3 = 0\n| totalcaps = 280 | totalgoals = 9\n| nationalyears1 = | nationalteam1 = | nationalcaps1 = | nationalgoals1 = \n| club-update =  \n| nationalteam-update = \n}}\n'''Jos\u00e9 Luis Ablanedo Iglesias''' ({{IPA-es|xo\u02c8se lwis a\u03b2la\u02c8ne\u00f0o}}; born 22 August 1962) is a Spanish former [[Association football|footballer]] who played as a [[Defender (association football)#Centre-back|central defender]].\n\n==Club career==\nBorn in [[Mieres, Asturias]], Ablanedo played the vast majority of his career with local [[Sporting de Gij\u00f3n]], making his senior debut whilst still a junior in a [[Copa del Rey]] match against amateurs [[CD Tur\u00f3n]], in November 1980.<ref>[http://hemeroteca.mundodeportivo.com/preview/1980/11/19/pagina-42/1063747/pdf.html 1\u20136: Gole\u00f3 el Sporting al Tur\u00f3n (1\u20136: Sporting routed Tur\u00f3n)]; [[Mundo Deportivo]], 19 November 1980 (in Spanish)</ref> He spent several years with [[Sporting de Gij\u00f3n B|the reserves]] in the lower leagues, and played his first [[La Liga]] game with the main squad on 22 April 1984 in a 0\u20133 away loss against [[Real Betis]].<ref>[http://hemeroteca.mundodeportivo.com/preview/1984/04/23/pagina-18/1106014/pdf.html 3\u20130: Festival Calder\u00f3n (3\u20130: Calder\u00f3n show)]; Mundo Deportivo, 23 April 1984 (in Spanish)</ref>\n\nAblanedo was definitely promoted to the first team for the [[1985\u201386 La Liga|1985\u201386 season]], and contributed with a career-best 43 matches and four goals as Sporting finished in fourth position [[1986\u201387 La Liga|the following campaign]]. He spent [[1991\u201392 La Liga|1991\u201392]] on loan to [[RCD Espanyol|RCD Espa\u00f1ol]], also in the top level,<ref>[http://hemeroteca.mundodeportivo.com/preview/1992/01/24/pagina-15/1244409/pdf.html Caras nuevas (New faces)]; Mundo Deportivo, 24 January 1992 (in Spanish)</ref> and retired with his main club in June 1994 at nearly 32 years of age.<ref>[http://tododeporte.elcomercio.es/asturias/2012-01-27/ingeniero-zaga-1004.html El ingeniero de la zaga (Defense engineer)]; [[El Comercio (Spain)|El Comercio]], 27 January 2012 (in Spanish)</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nAblanedo's younger brother, [[Juan Carlos Ablanedo|Juan Carlos]], was also a footballer. A [[Goalkeeper (association football)|goalkeeper]], he played solely for Sporting, and they were hence known as ''Ablanedo I'' and ''Ablanedo II''.<ref>[http://blogs.20minutos.es/quefuede/2008/06/20/quao-fue-de-ablanedo/ Qu\u00e9 fue de\u2026 Ablanedo (What happened to\u2026 Ablanedo)]; [[20 minutos]], 20 June 2008 (in Spanish)</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{BDFutbol|1456}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Ablanedo, Jose Luis}}\n[[Category:1962 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:People from Mieres, Asturias]]\n[[Category:Spanish footballers]]\n[[Category:Asturian footballers]]\n[[Category:Association football defenders]]\n[[Category:La Liga players]]\n[[Category:Segunda Divisi\u00f3n B players]]\n[[Category:Sporting de Gij\u00f3n B players]]\n[[Category:Sporting de Gij\u00f3n players]]\n[[Category:RCD Espanyol footballers]]\n", "text_old": "{{spanish name 2|Ablanedo|Iglesias}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2013}}\n{{Infobox football biography\n| name = Jos\u00e9 Luis Ablanedo\n| image = \n| fullname = Jos\u00e9 Luis Ablanedo Iglesias\n| birth_date = {{birth date and age|1962|8|22|df=y}}\n| birth_place = [[Mieres, Asturias|Mieres]], [[Spain]]\n| height = {{height|m=1.85}}\n| position = [[Defender (association football)#Centre-back|Centre back]]\n| currentclub = \n| clubnumber = \n| youthyears1 = | youthclubs1 = [[Sporting de Gij\u00f3n (youth)|Sporting Gij\u00f3n]]\n| years1 = 1981\u20131985 | clubs1 = [[Sporting de Gij\u00f3n B|Sporting B]] | caps1 = 98 | goals1 = 2\n| years2 = 1984\u20131994 | clubs2 = [[Sporting de Gij\u00f3n|Sporting Gij\u00f3n]] | caps2 = 174 | goals2 = 7\n| years3 = 1991\u20131992 | clubs3 = \u2192 [[RCD Espanyol|Espa\u00f1ol]] (loan) | caps3 = 8 | goals3 = 0\n| totalcaps = 280 | totalgoals = 9\n| nationalyears1 = | nationalteam1 = | nationalcaps1 = | nationalgoals1 = \n| club-update =  \n| nationalteam-update = \n}}\n'''Jos\u00e9 Luis Ablanedo Iglesias''' ({{IPA-es|xo\u02c8se lwis a\u03b2la\u02c8ne\u00f0o}}; born 22 August 1962) is a Spanish retired [[Association football|footballer]] who played as a [[Defender (association football)#Centre-back|central defender]].\n\n==Football career==\nBorn in [[Mieres, Asturias]], Ablanedo played the vast majority of his career with local [[Sporting de Gij\u00f3n]], making his senior debut whilst still a junior in a [[Copa del Rey]] match against amateurs [[CD Tur\u00f3n]], in November 1980.<ref>[http://hemeroteca.mundodeportivo.com/preview/1980/11/19/pagina-42/1063747/pdf.html 1\u20136: Gole\u00f3 el Sporting al Tur\u00f3n (1\u20136: Sporting routed Tur\u00f3n)]; [[Mundo Deportivo]], 19 November 1980 (in Spanish)</ref> He spent several years with [[Sporting de Gij\u00f3n B|the reserves]] in the lower leagues, and played his first [[La Liga]] game with the main squad on 22 April 1984 in a 0\u20133 away loss against [[Real Betis]].<ref>[http://hemeroteca.mundodeportivo.com/preview/1984/04/23/pagina-18/1106014/pdf.html 3\u20130: Festival Calder\u00f3n (3\u20130: Calder\u00f3n show)]; Mundo Deportivo, 23 April 1984 (in Spanish)</ref>\n\nAblanedo was definitely promoted to the first team for the [[1985\u201386 La Liga|1985\u201386 season]], and contributed with a career-best 43 matches and four goals as Sporting finished in fourth position [[1986\u201387 La Liga|the following campaign]]. He spent [[1991\u201392 La Liga|1991\u201392]] on loan to [[RCD Espanyol|RCD Espa\u00f1ol]], also in the top level,<ref>[http://hemeroteca.mundodeportivo.com/preview/1992/01/24/pagina-15/1244409/pdf.html Caras nuevas (New faces)]; Mundo Deportivo, 24 January 1992 (in Spanish)</ref> and retired with his main club in June 1994 at nearly 32 years of age.<ref>[http://tododeporte.elcomercio.es/asturias/2012-01-27/ingeniero-zaga-1004.html El ingeniero de la zaga (Defense engineer)]; [[El Comercio (Spain)|El Comercio]], 27 January 2012 (in Spanish)</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nAblanedo's younger brother, [[Juan Carlos Ablanedo|Juan Carlos]], was also a footballer. A [[Goalkeeper (association football)|goalkeeper]], he played solely for Sporting, and they were hence known as ''Ablanedo I'' and ''Ablanedo II''.<ref>[http://blogs.20minutos.es/quefuede/2008/06/20/quao-fue-de-ablanedo/ Qu\u00e9 fue de\u2026 Ablanedo (What happened to\u2026 Ablanedo)]; [[20 minutos]], 20 June 2008 (in Spanish)</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{BDFutbol|1456}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Ablanedo, Jose Luis}}\n[[Category:1962 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:People from Mieres, Asturias]]\n[[Category:Spanish footballers]]\n[[Category:Asturian footballers]]\n[[Category:Association football defenders]]\n[[Category:La Liga players]]\n[[Category:Segunda Divisi\u00f3n B players]]\n[[Category:Sporting de Gij\u00f3n B players]]\n[[Category:Sporting de Gij\u00f3n players]]\n