{"title_page": "Estuaries of Texas", "text_new": "{{Short description|Estuaries on the Gulf coast of Texas}}\n[[File:Texas estuaries map.png|thumb|alt=Map depicting the Gulf Coast of Texas, with coastal counties labeled and estuaries color-coded|Map of the major and minor estuaries of the Gulf Coast of Texas]]\nThe [[U.S. state]] of [[Texas]] has a '''series of estuaries''' along its coast on the [[Gulf of Mexico]], most of them bounded by the [[Texas barrier islands]]. [[Estuaries]] are coastal bodies of water in which [[freshwater]] from rivers mixes with [[saltwater]] from the sea. Twenty-one [[drainage basin]]s terminate along the Texas coastline, forming a chain of seven major and five minor estuaries: listed from southwest to northeast, these are the [[Rio Grande]] Estuary, [[Laguna Madre (United States)|Laguna Madre]], the [[Nueces River|Nueces]] Estuary ([[Corpus Christi Bay]]), the [[Mission River|Mission]]\u2013[[Aransas River|Aransas]] Estuary ([[Aransas Bay]]), the [[Guadalupe River (Texas)|Guadalupe]] Estuary ([[San Antonio Bay]]), the [[Colorado River (Texas)|Colorado]]\u2013[[Lavaca River|Lavaca]] Estuary ([[Matagorda Bay]]), [[East Matagorda Bay]], the [[San Bernard River]] and [[Cedar Lakes (Texas)|Cedar Lakes]] Estuary, the [[Brazos River]] Estuary, [[Christmas Bay (Texas)|Christmas Bay]], the [[Trinity River (Texas)|Trinity]]\u2013[[San Jacinto River (Texas)|San Jacinto]] Estuary ([[Galveston Bay]]), and the [[Sabine River (Texas\u2013Louisiana)|Sabine]]\u2013[[Neches River|Neches]] Estuary ([[Sabine Lake]]).<ref name=\"TWDB Main\">{{Cite web|title=Bays & Estuaries|website=[[Texas Water Development Board]]|url=https://www.twdb.texas.gov/surfacewater/bays/index.asp|accessdate=March 11, 2020}}</ref>\n\nThese water bodies include some of the largest and most ecologically productive coastal estuaries in the [[United States]] and contribute significantly to the ecological and economic resources of Texas.<ref name=\"TWDB Main\"/> They are included in a number of national protected areas such as [[National Wildlife Refuge]]s, a [[National Seashore]], and a [[National Estuarine Research Reserve]], as well as various [[state park]]s and other regional protected areas. The two most economically important (the Nueces and Trinity\u2013San Jacinto Estuaries) have been designated by the [[United States Environmental Protection Agency]] as estuaries of national significance under the [[National Estuary Program]]. The [[Gulf Intracoastal Waterway]] runs through each of the major estuaries, linking Texas ports with others along the [[Gulf Coast of the United States]].\n\n==Overview==\nThe seven major estuaries, listed from southwest to northeast, are the [[Laguna Madre (United States)|Laguna Madre]] Estuary, the [[Nueces River|Nueces]] Estuary, the [[Mission River|Mission]]\u2013[[Aransas River|Aransas]] Estuary, the [[Guadalupe River (Texas)|Guadalupe]] Estuary, the [[Colorado River (Texas)|Colorado]]\u2013[[Lavaca River|Lavaca]] Estuary, the [[Trinity River (Texas)|Trinity]]\u2013[[San Jacinto River (Texas)|San Jacinto]] Estuary, and the [[Sabine River (Texas\u2013Louisiana)|Sabine]]\u2013[[Neches River|Neches]] Estuary. Each estuary is named for its one or two chief contributing rivers, excepting Laguna Madre, which has no major river sources. The estuaries are also sometimes referred to by the names of their respective primary or central water bodies (Laguna Madre, [[Corpus Christi Bay]], [[Aransas Bay]], [[San Antonio Bay]], [[Matagorda Bay]], [[Galveston Bay]], and [[Sabine Lake]]), though each also includes smaller secondary bays, [[inlet]]s, or other marginal water bodies.<ref>{{Cite web|title=Major Estuaries of Texas|website=[[Texas Water Development Board]]|url=https://www.twdb.texas.gov/surfacewater/bays/major_estuaries/index.asp|accessdate=March 11, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Laguna Madre Estuary==\n{{Main|Laguna Madre (United States)}}\n[[File:Padre Island National Seashore - fishing in Laguna Madre.jpg|thumb|alt=A small boat and wading fishermen in shallow water by a beach|Sport fishing off [[Padre Island National Seashore]] in Laguna Madre]]\nThe Laguna Madre Estuary is located along the southern coast of Texas in [[Nueces County, Texas|Nueces]], [[Kenedy County, Texas|Kenedy]], [[Kleberg County, Texas|Kleberg]], [[Willacy County, Texas|Willacy]], and [[Cameron County, Texas|Cameron]] Counties, extending almost to the border with [[Mexico]].<ref>{{Cite web|title=Laguna Madre|website=[[Handbook of Texas Online]]|publisher=[[Texas State Historical Association]]|first=Art|last=Leatherwood|url=https://tshaonline.org/handbook/online/articles/rrl02|accessdate=March 11, 2020}}</ref> It is a long, shallow [[lagoon]] with no major river sources, separated from the [[Gulf of Mexico]] by [[Padre Island]] and [[Brazos Island]] and connecting with it through the [[Port Mansfield Channel]] and [[Brazos-Santiago Pass]]. Laguna Madre is the second largest of the Texas estuaries, approximately {{Convert|130|mi|km}} long and {{Convert|4|to|6|mi|km|0}} wide, with a surface area of {{Convert|280910|acre|ha}} including its westward extensions in [[Baffin Bay, Texas|Baffin Bay]] and [[South Bay (Texas)|South Bay]]. The lagoon is split by a {{convert|20|mi|km|adj=on}} stretch of [[sand flat]]s named the [[Saltillo Flats]], which divide it into \"upper\" (northern) and \"lower\" (southern) sections. The natural portions have an average depth of around {{Convert|4.5|ft|m}}, though deeper ship channels have been dredged through. Its low rate of freshwater recharge and high evaporation rate make it [[hypersaline]].<ref>{{Cite web|title=Laguna Madre|website=[[Texas Water Development Board]]|url=http://www.twdb.texas.gov/surfacewater/bays/major_estuaries/laguna_madre/index.asp|accessdate=March 11, 2020}}</ref>\n\nThe shores of the lagoon are sparsely populated, with the small towns of [[Port Isabel, Texas|Port Isabel]] and [[Port Mansfield, Texas|Port Mansfield]] on the mainland side and [[South Padre Island, Texas|South Padre Island]] on the barrier island as the only significant settlements; all three are located on the Lower Laguna Madre. [[Tourism]] and [[commercial fishing]] (especially for [[penaeid shrimp]]) are major industries in the region,<ref>{{Cite web|title=Port Isabel, Texas|website=[[Handbook of Texas Online]]|publisher=[[Texas State Historical Association]]|first=Alicia A.|last=Garza|url=https://tshaonline.org/handbook/online/articles/hgp09|accessdate=March 11, 2020}}</ref> and much of the mainland shore is part of [[King Ranch]]. The lagoon's rich ecosystem is maintained by a number of [[protected area]]s, including the [[Laguna Atascosa National Wildlife Refuge]] and [[Padre Island National Seashore]].<ref>{{Cite web|title=Laguna Atascosa National Wildlife Refuge Map|website=[[United States Fish and Wildlife Service]]|url=https://www.fws.gov/refuge/Laguna_Atascosa/map.html|accessdate=March 11, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|title=Padre Island National Seashore Map|website=[[United States National Park Service]]|url=https://www.nps.gov/pais/planyourvisit/maps.htm|accessdate=March 11, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Nueces Estuary==\n{{Main|Corpus Christi Bay}}\n[[File:AerialCorpusChristi.jpg|thumb|alt=Aerial photograph of an urban shoreline along a bay|[[Texas A&M University\u2013Corpus Christi]] on [[Ward Island (Texas)|Ward Island]] by the south shore of Corpus Christi Bay]]\nThe Nueces Estuary is located on the [[Texas Coastal Bend]] in [[San Patricio County, Texas|San Patricio]] and [[Nueces County, Texas|Nueces]] Counties, adjoining the city of [[Corpus Christi, Texas|Corpus Christi]]. It is fed by the [[Nueces River]] and [[Oso Creek (Texas)|Oso Creek]] and separated from the Gulf of Mexico by [[Mustang Island]].<ref name=\"CCB\">{{Cite web|title=Corpus Christi Bay|website=[[Handbook of Texas Online]]|publisher=[[Texas State Historical Association]]|first=Art|last=Leatherwood|url=https://tshaonline.org/handbook/online/articles/rrc05|accessdate=March 11, 2020}}</ref> The Nueces Estuary is the sixth largest of the Texas estuaries, with a surface area of {{Convert|106990|acre|ha}} including Corpus Christi Bay and its western and southern extensions in [[Nueces Bay]] and [[Oso Bay]].<ref>{{Cite web|title=Nueces Estuary (Corpus Christi Bay)|website=[[Texas Water Development Board]]|url=http://www.twdb.texas.gov/surfacewater/bays/major_estuaries/nueces/index.asp|accessdate=March 11, 2020}}</ref> The natural portions have a depth of up to {{Convert|13|ft|m|0}}.<ref>{{Cite web|title=Nueces and Mission\u2013Aransas Estuaries: A Study of the Influence of Freshwater Inflows|date=January 1981|publisher=[[Texas Department of Water Resources]]|website=[[Texas Water Development Board]]|url=http://www.twdb.texas.gov/surfacewater/bays/major_estuaries/mission_aransas/doc/LP-108.pdf|accessdate=March 11, 2020}}</ref>{{RP|III\u20131}} Smaller settlements around the bay include [[Portland, Texas|Portland]], [[Ingleside, Texas|Ingleside]], and [[Ingleside on the Bay, Texas|Ingleside on the Bay]], all located on the north shore.<ref>{{Cite web|title=Portland, Texas (San Patricio County)|website=[[Handbook of Texas Online]]|publisher=[[Texas State Historical Association]]|first=Keith|last=Guthrie|url=https://tshaonline.org/handbook/online/articles/hep09|accessdate=March 11, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|title=Ingleside, Texas (San Patricio County)|website=[[Handbook of Texas Online]]|publisher=[[Texas State Historical Association]]|first=Keith|last=Guthrie|url=https://tshaonline.org/handbook/online/articles/hfi01|accessdate=March 11, 2020}}</ref>\n\nCorpus Christi Bay is a deep-water [[natural harbor]], and the [[Maritime transport|shipping]] industry in the [[Port of Corpus Christi]] has been a major driver of human development in the region.<ref name=\"CCB\"/> Other significant industries include [[petroleum]] and [[natural gas]] extraction, tourism, commercial fishing, and military facilities such as [[Naval Air Station Corpus Christi]].<ref>{{Cite web|title=Corpus Christi, Texas|website=[[Handbook of Texas Online]]|publisher=[[Texas State Historical Association]]|first=Christopher|last=Long|url=https://tshaonline.org/handbook/online/articles/hdc03|accessdate=March 11, 2020}}</ref> The [[United States Environmental Protection Agency]] has designated the Nueces Estuary system as an estuary of national significance under the [[National Estuary Program]].<ref>{{Cite web|title=Coastal Bend Bays & Estuaries Program|url=https://www.cbbep.org/|accessdate=March 11, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Mission\u2013Aransas Estuary==\n{{Main|Aransas Bay}}\n[[File:Aransas Bay - panoramio.jpg|thumb|alt=Aerial photograph of a bay and islands with a paramotoring figure|Aerial view of [[San Jos\u00e9 Island (Texas)|San Jos\u00e9 Island]] and Aransas Bay]]\nThe Mission\u2013Aransas Estuary is located on the Texas Coastal Bend in [[Aransas County, Texas|Aransas]], [[Refugio County, Texas|Refugio]], and San Patricio Counties. It is fed by the [[Mission River|Mission]] and [[Aransas River|Aransas]] Rivers, separated from the Gulf of Mexico by [[San Jos\u00e9 Island (Texas)|San Jos\u00e9 Island]] and connecting with it through [[Aransas Pass]] and [[Cedar Bayou]]. The Mission\u2013Aransas Estuary is the fifth largest of the Texas estuaries, with a surface area of {{Convert|111780|acre|ha}} including Aransas Bay and its extensions in [[Redfish Bay]] to the southwest, [[Copano Bay]] to the northwest, and [[Saint Charles Bay]] to the north. The natural portions have an average depth of around {{Convert|5.5|ft|m|1}}.<ref>{{Cite web|title=Mission\u2013Aransas Estuary|website=[[Texas Water Development Board]]|url=http://www.twdb.texas.gov/surfacewater/bays/major_estuaries/mission_aransas/index.asp|accessdate=March 11, 2020}}</ref>\n\nThe shores of the estuary are sparsely populated, with the small towns of [[Aransas Pass, Texas|Aransas Pass]], [[Port Aransas, Texas|Port Aransas]], [[Rockport, Texas|Rockport]], and [[Fulton, Texas|Fulton]] as the only significant settlements. Historically Aransas Bay was a center for the [[meat packing]] industry, but today the region's economy centers around commercial fishing and tourism.<ref>{{Cite web|title=Aransas County|website=[[Handbook of Texas Online]]|publisher=[[Texas State Historical Association]]|first=Christopher|last=Long|url=https://tshaonline.org/handbook/online/articles/hca04|accessdate=March 11, 2020}}</ref> The Mission\u2013Aransas Estuary is the site of the [[Mission-Aransas National Estuarine Research Reserve]], the [[National Oceanic and Atmospheric Administration]]'s only [[National Estuarine Research Reserve]] in Texas. It serves as a wintering ground for the endangered [[whooping crane]].<ref>{{Cite web|title=Mission-Aransas National Estuarine Research Reserve|website=National Estuarine Research Reserves|url=https://coast.noaa.gov/nerrs/reserves/mission-aransas.html|accessdate=March 11, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Guadalupe Estuary==\n{{Main|San Antonio Bay}}\n[[File:20111216-NRCS-LSC-0388 - Flickr - USDAgov.jpg|thumb|Alt=Pelicans perch on pilings standing near a desolate grassy shoreline|Pelicans in [[Aransas National Wildlife Refuge]] by the shore of San Antonio Bay]]\nThe Guadalupe Estuary is located on the mid Texas coast in [[Calhoun County, Texas|Calhoun]], Aransas, and Refugio Counties. It is fed by the [[Guadalupe River (Texas)|Guadalupe River]], separated from the Gulf of Mexico by [[Matagorda Island]] and connecting with it through Cedar Bayou.<ref>{{Cite web|title=Guadalupe Estuary|website=[[Texas Water Development Board]]|url=http://www.twdb.texas.gov/surfacewater/bays/major_estuaries/guadalupe/index.asp|accessdate=March 11, 2020}}</ref> The Guadalupe Estuary is the fourth largest of the Texas estuaries, with a surface area of {{Convert|143000|acre|ha}} including San Antonio Bay and its extensions to the southwest and northeast in [[Mesquite Bay]] and [[Espiritu Santo Bay]]. The natural portions have an average depth of around {{Convert|2.5|ft|m|1}}.<ref>{{Cite web|title=Guadalupe Estuary: An Analysis of Bay Segment Boundaries, Physical Characteristics, and Nutrient Processes|publisher=[[Texas Department of Water Resources]]|website=[[Texas Water Development Board]]|date=March 1981|url=http://www.twdb.texas.gov/publications/reports/limited_printing/doc/LP-76.pdf|accessdate=March 11, 2020}}</ref>{{RP|6}}\n\nThe estuary is remote and difficult for shipping to access, and its shores are almost uninhabited, with the small towns of [[Seadrift, Texas|Seadrift]] and [[Austwell, Texas|Austwell]] as the only significant settlements. The leading industries in the region are [[oyster farming]], [[fish processing]] and the [[chemical industry]].<ref>{{Cite web|title=Seadrift, Texas|website=[[Handbook of Texas Online]]|publisher=[[Texas State Historical Association]]|first=Rebecca|last=Rubert|url=https://tshaonline.org/handbook/online/articles/hjs12|accessdate=March 11, 2020}}</ref> The southwestern shore and much of Matagorda Island are protected within the [[Aransas National Wildlife Refuge]].<ref>{{Cite web|title=San Antonio Bay|website=[[Handbook of Texas Online]]|publisher=[[Texas State Historical Association]]|first=Art|last=Leatherwood|url=https://tshaonline.org/handbook/online/articles/rrs03|accessdate=March 11, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Colorado\u2013Lavaca Estuary==\n{{Main|Matagorda Bay}}\n[[File:Harbor Palacios Texas.jpg|thumb|alt=Shrimping boats docked in rows in a harbor|Commercial [[shrimping]] vessels docked at Palacios, Texas, on Matagorda Bay]]\nThe Colorado\u2013Lavaca Estuary is located on the upper-mid Texas coast in [[Matagorda County, Texas|Matagorda]], [[Jackson County, Texas|Jackson]], [[Victoria County, Texas|Victoria]], and Calhoun Counties. It is fed by the [[Colorado River (Texas)|Colorado]], [[Lavaca River|Lavaca]], and [[Tres Palacios River|Tres Palacios]] Rivers, separated from the Gulf of Mexico by [[Matagorda Peninsula]] and connecting with it through [[Matagorda Ship Channel]] and [[Pass Cavallo (Texas)|Pass Cavallo]]. The Colorado\u2013Lavaca Estuary is the third largest of the Texas estuaries, with a surface area of {{Convert|244490|acre|ha}} including Matagorda Bay and its extensions in [[Lavaca Bay]] and several smaller bays.<ref>{{Cite web|title=Colorado\u2013Lavaca Estuary (Matagorda Bay)|website=[[Texas Water Development Board]]|url=http://www.twdb.texas.gov/surfacewater/bays/major_estuaries/colorado_lavaca/index.asp|accessdate=March 11, 2020}}</ref> The natural portions have depths ranging from {{Convert|6|to|13|ft|m|0}}.<ref>{{Cite web|title=Lavaca\u2013Tres Palacios Estuary: A Study of the Influence of Freshwater Inflows|publisher=[[Texas Department of Water Resources]]|website=[[Texas Water Development Board]]|date=June 1980|url=http://www.twdb.texas.gov/surfacewater/bays/major_estuaries/colorado_lavaca/doc/LP-106.pdf|accessdate=March 11, 2020}}</ref>{{RP|III\u20131}}\n\nThe shores of the estuary are sparsely populated, with the small towns of [[Port Lavaca, Texas|Port Lavaca]], [[Palacios, Texas|Palacios]], [[Port O'Connor, Texas|Port O'Connor]], and [[Point Comfort, Texas|Point Comfort]] as the only significant settlements.<ref>{{Cite web|title=Matagorda Bay|website=[[Handbook of Texas Online]]|publisher=[[Texas State Historical Association]]|first=Art|last=Leatherwood|url=https://tshaonline.org/handbook/online/articles/rbm28|accessdate=March 11, 2020}}</ref> Matagorda Bay is a major center for the commercial fishing and fish processing industries, with the [[Port of Port Lavaca \u2013 Point Comfort|Port of Port Lavaca]] driving much of the regional economy; tourism and manufacturing are also significant contributors.<ref>{{Cite web|title=Port Lavaca, Texas|website=[[Handbook of Texas Online]]|publisher=[[Texas State Historical Association]]|first=Lonnie Ficklen|last=Maywald|url=https://tshaonline.org/handbook/online/articles/hep07|accessdate=March 11, 2020}}</ref> The bay was the site of [[Ren\u00e9-Robert Cavelier, Sieur de La Salle|La Salle]]'s failed [[French colonization of Texas|French colony]], and the [[shipwreck]] of one of his ships, ''[[La Belle (ship)|La Belle]]'', was discovered and excavated in the 1990s and 2000s.<ref>{{Cite web|title=''La Belle'': The Ship That Changed History|website=[[Bullock Texas State History Museum]]|url=https://www.thestoryoftexas.com/la-belle/the-exhibit|accessdate=March 11, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Trinity\u2013San Jacinto Estuary==\n{{Main|Galveston Bay}}\n[[File:USS Texas and USCGC Manowar, in the Houston Ship Channel - 160803-G-CZ043-121.jpg|thumb|alt=A battleship docked in front of a stone obelisk overlooking a shipping channel|The [[San Jacinto Monument]] and [[USS Texas (BB-35)|USS ''Texas'']] by the [[Houston Ship Channel]] in Galveston Bay]]\nThe Trinity\u2013San Jacinto Estuary is located on the upper Texas coast in [[Chambers County, Texas|Chambers]], [[Harris County, Texas|Harris]], [[Galveston County, Texas|Galveston]], and [[Brazoria County, Texas|Brazoria]] Counties, adjoining the city of [[Houston]]. It is formed by the confluence of the [[Trinity River (Texas)|Trinity]] and [[San Jacinto River (Texas)|San Jacinto]] Rivers, separated from the Gulf of Mexico by [[Galveston Island]] and [[Bolivar Peninsula]] and connecting with it through [[Rollover Pass]], [[Bolivar Roads]], and [[San Luis Pass]]. The Trinity\u2013San Jacinto Estuary is the largest of the Texas estuaries, with a surface area of {{Convert|345280|acre|ha}} including Galveston Bay and its extensions in [[East Bay (Texas)|East Bay]] to the east, [[Trinity Bay (Texas)|Trinity Bay]] to the northeast, [[West Bay (Texas)|West Bay]] to the southwest, and several smaller bays and inlets.<ref>{{Cite web|title=Trinity\u2013San Jacinto Estuary (Galveston Bay)|website=[[Texas Water Development Board]]|url=https://www.twdb.texas.gov/surfacewater/bays/major_estuaries/trinity_san_jacinto/index.asp|accessdate=March 11, 2020}}</ref> The natural portions of the estuary have mean low-water depths ranging from {{Convert|6|to|10|ft|m|0}}.<ref name=\"TDWR Galveston\">{{Cite web|title=Trinity\u2013San Jacinto Estuary: A Study of the Influence of Freshwater Inflows|date=March 1981|publisher=[[Texas Department of Water Resources]]|website=[[Texas Water Development Board]]|url=https://www.twdb.texas.gov/surfacewater/bays/major_estuaries/trinity_san_jacinto/doc/LP-113.pdf|accessdate=March 11, 2020}}</ref>{{RP|III\u20131}}\n\nThe Trinity\u2013San Jacinto Estuary is almost surrounded by the [[Greater Houston]] urban area, and its shores are relatively urbanized and industrialized, especially to the west.<ref name=\"TDWR Galveston\"/>{{RP|III\u201312}} Other significant settlements on the shores include [[Baytown, Texas|Baytown]], [[Texas City, Texas|Texas City]], and [[Galveston, Texas|Galveston]].<ref>{{Cite web|title=Baytown, Texas|website=[[Handbook of Texas Online]]|publisher=[[Texas State Historical Association]]|first=Buck A.|last=Young|url=https://tshaonline.org/handbook/online/articles/hdb01|accessdate=March 11, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|title=Texas City, Texas|website=[[Handbook of Texas Online]]|publisher=[[Texas State Historical Association]]|first=Priscilla Myers|last=Benham|url=https://tshaonline.org/handbook/online/articles/hdt03|accessdate=March 11, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|title=Galveston, Texas|website=[[Handbook of Texas Online]]|publisher=[[Texas State Historical Association]]|first=David G.|last=McComb|url=https://tshaonline.org/handbook/online/articles/hdg01|accessdate=March 11, 2020}}</ref> The estuary is a major shipping center, the heart of the [[Houston Ship Channel]], and the [[Port of Houston]], [[Port of Texas City]], and [[Port of Galveston]] drive much economic activity on the waterways.<ref>{{Cite web|title=Houston Ship Channel|website=[[Handbook of Texas Online]]|publisher=[[Texas State Historical Association]]|first=Marilyn M.|last=Sibley|url=https://tshaonline.org/handbook/online/articles/rhh11|accessdate=March 11, 2020}}</ref> [[Petrochemical]] industries are concentrated along the western shore, and the estuary also supports Texas's largest commercial fishery.<ref name=\"TDWR Galveston\"/>{{RP|III\u201312,15}} The United States Environmental Protection Agency has designated the Trinity\u2013San Jacinto Estuary system as an estuary of national significance under the National Estuary Program.<ref>{{Cite web|title=Galveston Bay Estuary Program|url=https://gbep.texas.gov/|accessdate=March 11, 2020}}</ref> Portions of the northeastern shore are protected within the [[Anahuac National Wildlife Refuge]].<ref>{{Cite web|title=Anahuac National Wildlife Refuge Map|website=[[United States Fish and Wildlife Service]]|url=https://www.fws.gov/refuge/Anahuac/map.html|accessdate=March 11, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Sabine\u2013Neches Estuary==\n{{Main|Sabine Lake}}\n[[File:Dusk shot of an industrial scene along the road from Port Arthur to Sabine Pass, Texas LCCN2014630863.tif|thumb|alt=Oil refinery buildings along a waterway at night|[[Petrochemical]] industry along the Texas shore of Sabine Lake]]\nThe Sabine\u2013Neches Estuary is located on the [[Louisiana]] border at the corner of [[Southeast Texas]] in [[Jefferson County, Texas|Jefferson]] and [[Orange County, Texas|Orange]] Counties, adjoining the city of [[Port Arthur, Texas|Port Arthur]]. It is an almost totally enclosed [[lake]], formed by the confluence of the [[Neches River|Neches]] and [[Sabine River (Texas\u2013Louisiana)|Sabine]] Rivers and connecting to the Gulf of Mexico through [[Sabine Pass]]. The Sabine\u2013Neches Estuary is the smallest of the seven major estuaries, with a surface area of {{Convert|45320|acre|ha}} including Sabine Lake and a number of adjoining [[bayou]]s, and its small size and high rate of freshwater inflow make it the least saline of the seven.<ref>{{Cite web|title=Sabine-Neches Estuary|website=[[Texas Water Development Board]]|url=http://www.twdb.texas.gov/surfacewater/bays/major_estuaries/sabine_neches/index.asp|accessdate=February 11, 2020}}</ref> The natural portions of the estuary have a mean low-water depth of at most around {{Convert|10|ft|m|0}}.<ref name=\"TDWR Sabine\">{{Cite web|title=Sabine\u2013Neches Estuary: A Study of the Influence of Freshwater Inflows|date=July 1981|publisher=[[Texas Department of Water Resources]]|website=[[Texas Water Development Board]]|url=http://www.twdb.texas.gov/surfacewater/bays/major_estuaries/sabine_neches/doc/LP-116.pdf|accessdate=March 11, 2020}}</ref>{{RP|III\u20131}}\n\nThe channelization of the Sabine\u2013Neches Estuary has made it an important industrial waterway, the heart of the [[Sabine\u2013Neches Waterway]]. The three ports it links to the Gulf of Mexico (Port Arthur, [[Beaumont, Texas|Beaumont]], and [[Orange, Texas|Orange]]) form a major nexus for the shipping and petrochemical industries, the so-called [[Golden Triangle (Texas)|Golden Triangle]] of Texas.<ref>{{Cite web|title=Beaumont, Texas|website=[[Handbook of Texas Online]]|publisher=[[Texas State Historical Association]]|first=Paul E.|last=Isaac|url=https://tshaonline.org/handbook/online/articles/hdb02|accessdate=March 11, 2020}}</ref> The largest industries around the estuary are petroleum and natural gas extraction, [[petrochemical]] processing, shipping, and [[shipbuilding]]. Agriculture also forms a significant component of the regional economy, principally [[rice]] and [[soybean]] cultivation, [[livestock]] ranching, and commercial fishing (mainly for [[shellfish]]).<ref name=\"TDWR Sabine\"/>{{RP|III\u201320}}\n\n==Minor estuaries==\nTexas has five minor estuaries interspersed among its seven major estuary systems. These are smaller, less complicated estuaries with less significance to the state's hydrology, ecology, and economy. Several of these are simply the lower [[tidal reach]]es of particular rivers, without [[barrier islands]] or [[embayment]]s to separate them from the Gulf of Mexico.<ref>{{Cite web|title=Minor Estuaries of Texas|website=[[Texas Water Development Board]]|url=https://www.twdb.texas.gov/surfacewater/bays/minor_estuaries/index.asp|accessdate=March 11, 2020}}</ref>\n\n===Rio Grande Estuary===\nThe [[Rio Grande]] Estuary is located on the Texas\u2013Mexico border in Cameron County, south of Laguna Madre at the southern extremity of the Texas coast. It is a riverine estuary system consisting only of the lower reaches of the Rio Grande, with no associated bay.<ref>{{Cite web|title=Rio Grande Estuary|website=[[Texas Water Development Board]]|url=https://www.twdb.texas.gov/surfacewater/bays/minor_estuaries/rio_grande/index.asp|accessdate=March 11, 2020}}</ref>\n\n===East Matagorda Bay Estuary===\n{{Main|East Matagorda Bay}}\n[[East Matagorda Bay]] is a minor estuary located on the upper-mid Texas coast in Matagorda County immediately northeast of the Colorado\u2013Lavaca Estuary (Matagorda Bay). It has no significant river sources and is separated from the Gulf of Mexico by Matagorda Peninsula, only intermittently connecting with it through [[Brown Cedar Cut]]. The estuary has a surface area of {{Convert|37810|acre|ha}}, and its natural portions have an average depth of around {{Convert|3.4|ft|m|1}}<ref>{{Cite web|title=East Matagorda Bay|website=[[Texas Water Development Board]]|url=https://www.twdb.texas.gov/surfacewater/bays/minor_estuaries/east_matagorda/index.asp|accessdate=March 11, 2020}}</ref>\n\n===San Bernard River and Cedar Lakes Estuary===\nThe [[San Bernard River]] and [[Cedar Lakes (Texas)|Cedar Lakes]] Estuary is one of three minor estuaries located on the upper-mid Texas coast in Brazoria County between Matagorda Bay and Galveston Bay. It includes Cedar Lakes, [[Cowtrap Lake]], and the lower reaches of the San Bernard River, covering a surface area of {{Convert|3760|acre|ha}} with an average depth of {{Convert|2.1|ft|m|1}}.<ref>{{Cite web|title=San Bernard River and Cedar Lakes Estuary|website=[[Texas Water Development Board]]|url=https://www.twdb.texas.gov/surfacewater/bays/minor_estuaries/san_bernard/index.asp|accessdate=March 11, 2020}}</ref>\n\n===Brazos River Estuary===\nThe [[Brazos River]] Estuary is the second of three minor estuaries located on the upper-mid Texas coast in Brazoria County between Matagorda Bay and Galveston Bay. It is a riverine estuary system consisting only of the lower reaches of the Brazos River, with no associated bay.<ref>{{Cite web|title=Brazos River Estuary|website=[[Texas Water Development Board]]|url=https://www.twdb.texas.gov/surfacewater/bays/minor_estuaries/brazos/index.asp|accessdate=March 11, 2020}}</ref>\n\n===Christmas Bay Estuary===\n{{Main|Christmas Bay (Texas)}}\n[[Christmas Bay (Texas)|Christmas Bay]] is a minor estuary located on the upper-mid Texas coast in Brazoria County immediately southwest of the Trinity\u2013San Jacinto Estuary (Galveston Bay). It is fed by [[Bastrop Bayou]], separated from the Gulf of Mexico by [[Follet's Island]] and connecting with it through San Luis Pass and [[Cold Pass]]. Its minor extensions are [[Bastrop Bay]] to the north and [[Drum Bay]] to the southwest.<ref>{{Cite web|title=Christmas Bay|website=[[Texas Water Development Board]]|url=https://www.twdb.texas.gov/surfacewater/bays/minor_estuaries/christmas/index.asp|accessdate=March 11, 2020}}</ref> The estuary has a surface area of {{Convert|4173|acre|ha}}. Much of its shoreline is protected within the [[Brazoria National Wildlife Refuge]].<ref>{{Cite web|title=Texas GEMS \u2014 Christmas Bay Coastal Preserve|website=[[Texas Parks and Wildlife Department]]|url=https://tpwd.texas.gov/landwater/water/conservation/txgems/christma/index.phtml|accessdate=April 2, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{Commonscat-inline|Estuaries of Texas}}\n\n{{Estuaries of Texas}}\n\n[[Category:Estuaries of Texas| ]]\n", "text_old": "{{Short description|Estuaries on the Gulf coast of Texas}}\n[[File:Texas estuaries map.png|thumb|alt=Map depicting the Gulf Coast of Texas, with coastal counties labeled and estuaries color-coded|Map of the major and minor estuaries of the Gulf Coast of Texas]]\nThe [[U.S. state]] of [[Texas]] has a '''series of estuaries''' along its coast on the [[Gulf of Mexico]], most of them bounded by the [[Texas barrier islands]]. [[Estuaries]] are coastal bodies of water in which [[freshwater]] from rivers mixes with [[saltwater]] from the sea. Twenty-one [[drainage basin]]s terminate along the Texas coastline, forming a chain of seven major and five minor estuaries: listed from southwest to northeast, these are the [[Rio Grande]] Estuary, [[Laguna Madre (United States)|Laguna Madre]], the [[Nueces River|Nueces]] Estuary ([[Corpus Christi Bay]]), the [[Mission River|Mission]]\u2013[[Aransas River|Aransas]] Estuary ([[Aransas Bay]]), the [[Guadalupe River (Texas)|Guadalupe]] Estuary ([[San Antonio Bay]]), the [[Colorado River (Texas)|Colorado]]\u2013[[Lavaca River|Lavaca]] Estuary ([[Matagorda Bay]]), [[East Matagorda Bay]], the [[San Bernard River]] and [[Cedar Lakes (Texas)|Cedar Lakes]] Estuary, the [[Brazos River]] Estuary, [[Christmas Bay]], the [[Trinity River (Texas)|Trinity]]\u2013[[San Jacinto River (Texas)|San Jacinto]] Estuary ([[Galveston Bay]]), and the [[Sabine River (Texas\u2013Louisiana)|Sabine]]\u2013[[Neches River|Neches]] Estuary ([[Sabine Lake]]).<ref name=\"TWDB Main\">{{Cite web|title=Bays & Estuaries|website=[[Texas Water Development Board]]|url=https://www.twdb.texas.gov/surfacewater/bays/index.asp|accessdate=March 11, 2020}}</ref>\n\nThese water bodies include some of the largest and most ecologically productive coastal estuaries in the [[United States]] and contribute significantly to the ecological and economic resources of Texas.<ref name=\"TWDB Main\"/> They are included in a number of national protected areas such as [[National Wildlife Refuge]]s, a [[National Seashore]], and a [[National Estuarine Research Reserve]], as well as various [[state park]]s and other regional protected areas. The two most economically important (the Nueces and Trinity\u2013San Jacinto Estuaries) have been designated by the [[United States Environmental Protection Agency]] as estuaries of national significance under the [[National Estuary Program]]. The [[Gulf Intracoastal Waterway]] runs through each of the major estuaries, linking Texas ports with others along the [[Gulf Coast of the United States]].\n\n==Overview==\nThe seven major estuaries, listed from southwest to northeast, are the [[Laguna Madre (United States)|Laguna Madre]] Estuary, the [[Nueces River|Nueces]] Estuary, the [[Mission River|Mission]]\u2013[[Aransas River|Aransas]] Estuary, the [[Guadalupe River (Texas)|Guadalupe]] Estuary, the [[Colorado River (Texas)|Colorado]]\u2013[[Lavaca River|Lavaca]] Estuary, the [[Trinity River (Texas)|Trinity]]\u2013[[San Jacinto River (Texas)|San Jacinto]] Estuary, and the [[Sabine River (Texas\u2013Louisiana)|Sabine]]\u2013[[Neches River|Neches]] Estuary. Each estuary is named for its one or two chief contributing rivers, excepting Laguna Madre, which has no major river sources. The estuaries are also sometimes referred to by the names of their respective primary or central water bodies (Laguna Madre, [[Corpus Christi Bay]], [[Aransas Bay]], [[San Antonio Bay]], [[Matagorda Bay]], [[Galveston Bay]], and [[Sabine Lake]]), though each also includes smaller secondary bays, [[inlet]]s, or other marginal water bodies.<ref>{{Cite web|title=Major Estuaries of Texas|website=[[Texas Water Development Board]]|url=https://www.twdb.texas.gov/surfacewater/bays/major_estuaries/index.asp|accessdate=March 11, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Laguna Madre Estuary==\n{{Main|Laguna Madre (United States)}}\n[[File:Padre Island National Seashore - fishing in Laguna Madre.jpg|thumb|alt=A small boat and wading fishermen in shallow water by a beach|Sport fishing off [[Padre Island National Seashore]] in Laguna Madre]]\nThe Laguna Madre Estuary is located along the southern coast of Texas in [[Nueces County, Texas|Nueces]], [[Kenedy County, Texas|Kenedy]], [[Kleberg County, Texas|Kleberg]], [[Willacy County, Texas|Willacy]], and [[Cameron County, Texas|Cameron]] Counties, extending almost to the border with [[Mexico]].<ref>{{Cite web|title=Laguna Madre|website=[[Handbook of Texas Online]]|publisher=[[Texas State Historical Association]]|first=Art|last=Leatherwood|url=https://tshaonline.org/handbook/online/articles/rrl02|accessdate=March 11, 2020}}</ref> It is a long, shallow [[lagoon]] with no major river sources, separated from the [[Gulf of Mexico]] by [[Padre Island]] and [[Brazos Island]] and connecting with it through the [[Port Mansfield Channel]] and [[Brazos-Santiago Pass]]. Laguna Madre is the second largest of the Texas estuaries, approximately {{Convert|130|mi|km}} long and {{Convert|4|to|6|mi|km|0}} wide, with a surface area of {{Convert|280910|acre|ha}} including its westward extensions in [[Baffin Bay, Texas|Baffin Bay]] and [[South Bay (Texas)|South Bay]]. The lagoon is split by a {{convert|20|mi|km|adj=on}} stretch of [[sand flat]]s named the [[Saltillo Flats]], which divide it into \"upper\" (northern) and \"lower\" (southern) sections. The natural portions have an average depth of around {{Convert|4.5|ft|m}}, though deeper ship channels have been dredged through. Its low rate of freshwater recharge and high evaporation rate make it [[hypersaline]].<ref>{{Cite web|title=Laguna Madre|website=[[Texas Water Development Board]]|url=http://www.twdb.texas.gov/surfacewater/bays/major_estuaries/laguna_madre/index.asp|accessdate=March 11, 2020}}</ref>\n\nThe shores of the lagoon are sparsely populated, with the small towns of [[Port Isabel, Texas|Port Isabel]] and [[Port Mansfield, Texas|Port Mansfield]] on the mainland side and [[South Padre Island, Texas|South Padre Island]] on the barrier island as the only significant settlements; all three are located on the Lower Laguna Madre. [[Tourism]] and [[commercial fishing]] (especially for [[penaeid shrimp]]) are major industries in the region,<ref>{{Cite web|title=Port Isabel, Texas|website=[[Handbook of Texas Online]]|publisher=[[Texas State Historical Association]]|first=Alicia A.|last=Garza|url=https://tshaonline.org/handbook/online/articles/hgp09|accessdate=March 11, 2020}}</ref> and much of the mainland shore is part of [[King Ranch]]. The lagoon's rich ecosystem is maintained by a number of [[protected area]]s, including the [[Laguna Atascosa National Wildlife Refuge]] and [[Padre Island National Seashore]].<ref>{{Cite web|title=Laguna Atascosa National Wildlife Refuge Map|website=[[United States Fish and Wildlife Service]]|url=https://www.fws.gov/refuge/Laguna_Atascosa/map.html|accessdate=March 11, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|title=Padre Island National Seashore Map|website=[[United States National Park Service]]|url=https://www.nps.gov/pais/planyourvisit/maps.htm|accessdate=March 11, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Nueces Estuary==\n{{Main|Corpus Christi Bay}}\n[[File:AerialCorpusChristi.jpg|thumb|alt=Aerial photograph of an urban shoreline along a bay|[[Texas A&M University\u2013Corpus Christi]] on [[Ward Island (Texas)|Ward Island]] by the south shore of Corpus Christi Bay]]\nThe Nueces Estuary is located on the [[Texas Coastal Bend]] in [[San Patricio County, Texas|San Patricio]] and [[Nueces County, Texas|Nueces]] Counties, adjoining the city of [[Corpus Christi, Texas|Corpus Christi]]. It is fed by the [[Nueces River]] and [[Oso Creek (Texas)|Oso Creek]] and separated from the Gulf of Mexico by [[Mustang Island]].<ref name=\"CCB\">{{Cite web|title=Corpus Christi Bay|website=[[Handbook of Texas Online]]|publisher=[[Texas State Historical Association]]|first=Art|last=Leatherwood|url=https://tshaonline.org/handbook/online/articles/rrc05|accessdate=March 11, 2020}}</ref> The Nueces Estuary is the sixth largest of the Texas estuaries, with a surface area of {{Convert|106990|acre|ha}} including Corpus Christi Bay and its western and southern extensions in [[Nueces Bay]] and [[Oso Bay]].<ref>{{Cite web|title=Nueces Estuary (Corpus Christi Bay)|website=[[Texas Water Development Board]]|url=http://www.twdb.texas.gov/surfacewater/bays/major_estuaries/nueces/index.asp|accessdate=March 11, 2020}}</ref> The natural portions have a depth of up to {{Convert|13|ft|m|0}}.<ref>{{Cite web|title=Nueces and Mission\u2013Aransas Estuaries: A Study of the Influence of Freshwater Inflows|date=January 1981|publisher=[[Texas Department of Water Resources]]|website=[[Texas Water Development Board]]|url=http://www.twdb.texas.gov/surfacewater/bays/major_estuaries/mission_aransas/doc/LP-108.pdf|accessdate=March 11, 2020}}</ref>{{RP|III\u20131}} Smaller settlements around the bay include [[Portland, Texas|Portland]], [[Ingleside, Texas|Ingleside]], and [[Ingleside on the Bay, Texas|Ingleside on the Bay]], all located on the north shore.<ref>{{Cite web|title=Portland, Texas (San Patricio County)|website=[[Handbook of Texas Online]]|publisher=[[Texas State Historical Association]]|first=Keith|last=Guthrie|url=https://tshaonline.org/handbook/online/articles/hep09|accessdate=March 11, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|title=Ingleside, Texas (San Patricio County)|website=[[Handbook of Texas Online]]|publisher=[[Texas State Historical Association]]|first=Keith|last=Guthrie|url=https://tshaonline.org/handbook/online/articles/hfi01|accessdate=March 11, 2020}}</ref>\n\nCorpus Christi Bay is a deep-water [[natural harbor]], and the [[Maritime transport|shipping]] industry in the [[Port of Corpus Christi]] has been a major driver of human development in the region.<ref name=\"CCB\"/> Other significant industries include [[petroleum]] and [[natural gas]] extraction, tourism, commercial fishing, and military facilities such as [[Naval Air Station Corpus Christi]].<ref>{{Cite web|title=Corpus Christi, Texas|website=[[Handbook of Texas Online]]|publisher=[[Texas State Historical Association]]|first=Christopher|last=Long|url=https://tshaonline.org/handbook/online/articles/hdc03|accessdate=March 11, 2020}}</ref> The [[United States Environmental Protection Agency]] has designated the Nueces Estuary system as an estuary of national significance under the [[National Estuary Program]].<ref>{{Cite web|title=Coastal Bend Bays & Estuaries Program|url=https://www.cbbep.org/|accessdate=March 11, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Mission\u2013Aransas Estuary==\n{{Main|Aransas Bay}}\n[[File:Aransas Bay - panoramio.jpg|thumb|alt=Aerial photograph of a bay and islands with a paramotoring figure|Aerial view of [[San Jos\u00e9 Island (Texas)|San Jos\u00e9 Island]] and Aransas Bay]]\nThe Mission\u2013Aransas Estuary is located on the Texas Coastal Bend in [[Aransas County, Texas|Aransas]], [[Refugio County, Texas|Refugio]], and San Patricio Counties. It is fed by the [[Mission River|Mission]] and [[Aransas River|Aransas]] Rivers, separated from the Gulf of Mexico by [[San Jos\u00e9 Island (Texas)|San Jos\u00e9 Island]] and connecting with it through [[Aransas Pass]] and [[Cedar Bayou]]. The Mission\u2013Aransas Estuary is the fifth largest of the Texas estuaries, with a surface area of {{Convert|111780|acre|ha}} including Aransas Bay and its extensions in [[Redfish Bay]] to the southwest, [[Copano Bay]] to the northwest, and [[Saint Charles Bay]] to the north. The natural portions have an average depth of around {{Convert|5.5|ft|m|1}}.<ref>{{Cite web|title=Mission\u2013Aransas Estuary|website=[[Texas Water Development Board]]|url=http://www.twdb.texas.gov/surfacewater/bays/major_estuaries/mission_aransas/index.asp|accessdate=March 11, 2020}}</ref>\n\nThe shores of the estuary are sparsely populated, with the small towns of [[Aransas Pass, Texas|Aransas Pass]], [[Port Aransas, Texas|Port Aransas]], [[Rockport, Texas|Rockport]], and [[Fulton, Texas|Fulton]] as the only significant settlements. Historically Aransas Bay was a center for the [[meat packing]] industry, but today the region's economy centers around commercial fishing and tourism.<ref>{{Cite web|title=Aransas County|website=[[Handbook of Texas Online]]|publisher=[[Texas State Historical Association]]|first=Christopher|last=Long|url=https://tshaonline.org/handbook/online/articles/hca04|accessdate=March 11, 2020}}</ref> The Mission\u2013Aransas Estuary is the site of the [[Mission-Aransas National Estuarine Research Reserve]], the [[National Oceanic and Atmospheric Administration]]'s only [[National Estuarine Research Reserve]] in Texas. It serves as a wintering ground for the endangered [[whooping crane]].<ref>{{Cite web|title=Mission-Aransas National Estuarine Research Reserve|website=National Estuarine Research Reserves|url=https://coast.noaa.gov/nerrs/reserves/mission-aransas.html|accessdate=March 11, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Guadalupe Estuary==\n{{Main|San Antonio Bay}}\n[[File:20111216-NRCS-LSC-0388 - Flickr - USDAgov.jpg|thumb|Alt=Pelicans perch on pilings standing near a desolate grassy shoreline|Pelicans in [[Aransas National Wildlife Refuge]] by the shore of San Antonio Bay]]\nThe Guadalupe Estuary is located on the mid Texas coast in [[Calhoun County, Texas|Calhoun]], Aransas, and Refugio Counties. It is fed by the [[Guadalupe River (Texas)|Guadalupe River]], separated from the Gulf of Mexico by [[Matagorda Island]] and connecting with it through Cedar Bayou.<ref>{{Cite web|title=Guadalupe Estuary|website=[[Texas Water Development Board]]|url=http://www.twdb.texas.gov/surfacewater/bays/major_estuaries/guadalupe/index.asp|accessdate=March 11, 2020}}</ref> The Guadalupe Estuary is the fourth largest of the Texas estuaries, with a surface area of {{Convert|143000|acre|ha}} including San Antonio Bay and its extensions to the southwest and northeast in [[Mesquite Bay]] and [[Espiritu Santo Bay]]. The natural portions have an average depth of around {{Convert|2.5|ft|m|1}}.<ref>{{Cite web|title=Guadalupe Estuary: An Analysis of Bay Segment Boundaries, Physical Characteristics, and Nutrient Processes|publisher=[[Texas Department of Water Resources]]|website=[[Texas Water Development Board]]|date=March 1981|url=http://www.twdb.texas.gov/publications/reports/limited_printing/doc/LP-76.pdf|accessdate=March 11, 2020}}</ref>{{RP|6}}\n\nThe estuary is remote and difficult for shipping to access, and its shores are almost uninhabited, with the small towns of [[Seadrift, Texas|Seadrift]] and [[Austwell, Texas|Austwell]] as the only significant settlements. The leading industries in the region are [[oyster farming]], [[fish processing]] and the [[chemical industry]].<ref>{{Cite web|title=Seadrift, Texas|website=[[Handbook of Texas Online]]|publisher=[[Texas State Historical Association]]|first=Rebecca|last=Rubert|url=https://tshaonline.org/handbook/online/articles/hjs12|accessdate=March 11, 2020}}</ref> The southwestern shore and much of Matagorda Island are protected within the [[Aransas National Wildlife Refuge]].<ref>{{Cite web|title=San Antonio Bay|website=[[Handbook of Texas Online]]|publisher=[[Texas State Historical Association]]|first=Art|last=Leatherwood|url=https://tshaonline.org/handbook/online/articles/rrs03|accessdate=March 11, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Colorado\u2013Lavaca Estuary==\n{{Main|Matagorda Bay}}\n[[File:Harbor Palacios Texas.jpg|thumb|alt=Shrimping boats docked in rows in a harbor|Commercial [[shrimping]] vessels docked at Palacios, Texas, on Matagorda Bay]]\nThe Colorado\u2013Lavaca Estuary is located on the upper-mid Texas coast in [[Matagorda County, Texas|Matagorda]], [[Jackson County, Texas|Jackson]], [[Victoria County, Texas|Victoria]], and Calhoun Counties. It is fed by the [[Colorado River (Texas)|Colorado]], [[Lavaca River|Lavaca]], and [[Tres Palacios River|Tres Palacios]] Rivers, separated from the Gulf of Mexico by [[Matagorda Peninsula]] and connecting with it through [[Matagorda Ship Channel]] and [[Pass Cavallo (Texas)|Pass Cavallo]]. The Colorado\u2013Lavaca Estuary is the third largest of the Texas estuaries, with a surface area of {{Convert|244490|acre|ha}} including Matagorda Bay and its extensions in [[Lavaca Bay]] and several smaller bays.<ref>{{Cite web|title=Colorado\u2013Lavaca Estuary (Matagorda Bay)|website=[[Texas Water Development Board]]|url=http://www.twdb.texas.gov/surfacewater/bays/major_estuaries/colorado_lavaca/index.asp|accessdate=March 11, 2020}}</ref> The natural portions have depths ranging from {{Convert|6|to|13|ft|m|0}}.<ref>{{Cite web|title=Lavaca\u2013Tres Palacios Estuary: A Study of the Influence of Freshwater Inflows|publisher=[[Texas Department of Water Resources]]|website=[[Texas Water Development Board]]|date=June 1980|url=http://www.twdb.texas.gov/surfacewater/bays/major_estuaries/colorado_lavaca/doc/LP-106.pdf|accessdate=March 11, 2020}}</ref>{{RP|III\u20131}}\n\nThe shores of the estuary are sparsely populated, with the small towns of [[Port Lavaca, Texas|Port Lavaca]], [[Palacios, Texas|Palacios]], [[Port O'Connor, Texas|Port O'Connor]], and [[Point Comfort, Texas|Point Comfort]] as the only significant settlements.<ref>{{Cite web|title=Matagorda Bay|website=[[Handbook of Texas Online]]|publisher=[[Texas State Historical Association]]|first=Art|last=Leatherwood|url=https://tshaonline.org/handbook/online/articles/rbm28|accessdate=March 11, 2020}}</ref> Matagorda Bay is a major center for the commercial fishing and fish processing industries, with the [[Port of Port Lavaca \u2013 Point Comfort|Port of Port Lavaca]] driving much of the regional economy; tourism and manufacturing are also significant contributors.<ref>{{Cite web|title=Port Lavaca, Texas|website=[[Handbook of Texas Online]]|publisher=[[Texas State Historical Association]]|first=Lonnie Ficklen|last=Maywald|url=https://tshaonline.org/handbook/online/articles/hep07|accessdate=March 11, 2020}}</ref> The bay was the site of [[Ren\u00e9-Robert Cavelier, Sieur de La Salle|La Salle]]'s failed [[French colonization of Texas|French colony]], and the [[shipwreck]] of one of his ships, ''[[La Belle (ship)|La Belle]]'', was discovered and excavated in the 1990s and 2000s.<ref>{{Cite web|title=''La Belle'': The Ship That Changed History|website=[[Bullock Texas State History Museum]]|url=https://www.thestoryoftexas.com/la-belle/the-exhibit|accessdate=March 11, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Trinity\u2013San Jacinto Estuary==\n{{Main|Galveston Bay}}\n[[File:USS Texas and USCGC Manowar, in the Houston Ship Channel - 160803-G-CZ043-121.jpg|thumb|alt=A battleship docked in front of a stone obelisk overlooking a shipping channel|The [[San Jacinto Monument]] and [[USS Texas (BB-35)|USS ''Texas'']] by the [[Houston Ship Channel]] in Galveston Bay]]\nThe Trinity\u2013San Jacinto Estuary is located on the upper Texas coast in [[Chambers County, Texas|Chambers]], [[Harris County, Texas|Harris]], [[Galveston County, Texas|Galveston]], and [[Brazoria County, Texas|Brazoria]] Counties, adjoining the city of [[Houston]]. It is formed by the confluence of the [[Trinity River (Texas)|Trinity]] and [[San Jacinto River (Texas)|San Jacinto]] Rivers, separated from the Gulf of Mexico by [[Galveston Island]] and [[Bolivar Peninsula]] and connecting with it through [[Rollover Pass]], [[Bolivar Roads]], and [[San Luis Pass]]. The Trinity\u2013San Jacinto Estuary is the largest of the Texas estuaries, with a surface area of {{Convert|345280|acre|ha}} including Galveston Bay and its extensions in [[East Bay (Texas)|East Bay]] to the east, [[Trinity Bay (Texas)|Trinity Bay]] to the northeast, [[West Bay (Texas)|West Bay]] to the southwest, and several smaller bays and inlets.<ref>{{Cite web|title=Trinity\u2013San Jacinto Estuary (Galveston Bay)|website=[[Texas Water Development Board]]|url=https://www.twdb.texas.gov/surfacewater/bays/major_estuaries/trinity_san_jacinto/index.asp|accessdate=March 11, 2020}}</ref> The natural portions of the estuary have mean low-water depths ranging from {{Convert|6|to|10|ft|m|0}}.<ref name=\"TDWR Galveston\">{{Cite web|title=Trinity\u2013San Jacinto Estuary: A Study of the Influence of Freshwater Inflows|date=March 1981|publisher=[[Texas Department of Water Resources]]|website=[[Texas Water Development Board]]|url=https://www.twdb.texas.gov/surfacewater/bays/major_estuaries/trinity_san_jacinto/doc/LP-113.pdf|accessdate=March 11, 2020}}</ref>{{RP|III\u20131}}\n\nThe Trinity\u2013San Jacinto Estuary is almost surrounded by the [[Greater Houston]] urban area, and its shores are relatively urbanized and industrialized, especially to the west.<ref name=\"TDWR Galveston\"/>{{RP|III\u201312}} Other significant settlements on the shores include [[Baytown, Texas|Baytown]], [[Texas City, Texas|Texas City]], and [[Galveston, Texas|Galveston]].<ref>{{Cite web|title=Baytown, Texas|website=[[Handbook of Texas Online]]|publisher=[[Texas State Historical Association]]|first=Buck A.|last=Young|url=https://tshaonline.org/handbook/online/articles/hdb01|accessdate=March 11, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|title=Texas City, Texas|website=[[Handbook of Texas Online]]|publisher=[[Texas State Historical Association]]|first=Priscilla Myers|last=Benham|url=https://tshaonline.org/handbook/online/articles/hdt03|accessdate=March 11, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|title=Galveston, Texas|website=[[Handbook of Texas Online]]|publisher=[[Texas State Historical Association]]|first=David G.|last=McComb|url=https://tshaonline.org/handbook/online/articles/hdg01|accessdate=March 11, 2020}}</ref> The estuary is a major shipping center, the heart of the [[Houston Ship Channel]], and the [[Port of Houston]], [[Port of Texas City]], and [[Port of Galveston]] drive much economic activity on the waterways.<ref>{{Cite web|title=Houston Ship Channel|website=[[Handbook of Texas Online]]|publisher=[[Texas State Historical Association]]|first=Marilyn M.|last=Sibley|url=https://tshaonline.org/handbook/online/articles/rhh11|accessdate=March 11, 2020}}</ref> [[Petrochemical]] industries are concentrated along the western shore, and the estuary also supports Texas's largest commercial fishery.<ref name=\"TDWR Galveston\"/>{{RP|III\u201312,15}} The United States Environmental Protection Agency has designated the Trinity\u2013San Jacinto Estuary system as an estuary of national significance under the National Estuary Program.<ref>{{Cite web|title=Galveston Bay Estuary Program|url=https://gbep.texas.gov/|accessdate=March 11, 2020}}</ref> Portions of the northeastern shore are protected within the [[Anahuac National Wildlife Refuge]].<ref>{{Cite web|title=Anahuac National Wildlife Refuge Map|website=[[United States Fish and Wildlife Service]]|url=https://www.fws.gov/refuge/Anahuac/map.html|accessdate=March 11, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Sabine\u2013Neches Estuary==\n{{Main|Sabine Lake}}\n[[File:Dusk shot of an industrial scene along the road from Port Arthur to Sabine Pass, Texas LCCN2014630863.tif|thumb|alt=Oil refinery buildings along a waterway at night|[[Petrochemical]] industry along the Texas shore of Sabine Lake]]\nThe Sabine\u2013Neches Estuary is located on the [[Louisiana]] border at the corner of [[Southeast Texas]] in [[Jefferson County, Texas|Jefferson]] and [[Orange County, Texas|Orange]] Counties, adjoining the city of [[Port Arthur, Texas|Port Arthur]]. It is an almost totally enclosed [[lake]], formed by the confluence of the [[Neches River|Neches]] and [[Sabine River (Texas\u2013Louisiana)|Sabine]] Rivers and connecting to the Gulf of Mexico through [[Sabine Pass]]. The Sabine\u2013Neches Estuary is the smallest of the seven major estuaries, with a surface area of {{Convert|45320|acre|ha}} including Sabine Lake and a number of adjoining [[bayou]]s, and its small size and high rate of freshwater inflow make it the least saline of the seven.<ref>{{Cite web|title=Sabine-Neches Estuary|website=[[Texas Water Development Board]]|url=http://www.twdb.texas.gov/surfacewater/bays/major_estuaries/sabine_neches/index.asp|accessdate=February 11, 2020}}</ref> The natural portions of the estuary have a mean low-water depth of at most around {{Convert|10|ft|m|0}}.<ref name=\"TDWR Sabine\">{{Cite web|title=Sabine\u2013Neches Estuary: A Study of the Influence of Freshwater Inflows|date=July 1981|publisher=[[Texas Department of Water Resources]]|website=[[Texas Water Development Board]]|url=http://www.twdb.texas.gov/surfacewater/bays/major_estuaries/sabine_neches/doc/LP-116.pdf|accessdate=March 11, 2020}}</ref>{{RP|III\u20131}}\n\nThe channelization of the Sabine\u2013Neches Estuary has made it an important industrial waterway, the heart of the [[Sabine\u2013Neches Waterway]]. The three ports it links to the Gulf of Mexico (Port Arthur, [[Beaumont, Texas|Beaumont]], and [[Orange, Texas|Orange]]) form a major nexus for the shipping and petrochemical industries, the so-called [[Golden Triangle (Texas)|Golden Triangle]] of Texas.<ref>{{Cite web|title=Beaumont, Texas|website=[[Handbook of Texas Online]]|publisher=[[Texas State Historical Association]]|first=Paul E.|last=Isaac|url=https://tshaonline.org/handbook/online/articles/hdb02|accessdate=March 11, 2020}}</ref> The largest industries around the estuary are petroleum and natural gas extraction, [[petrochemical]] processing, shipping, and [[shipbuilding]]. Agriculture also forms a significant component of the regional economy, principally [[rice]] and [[soybean]] cultivation, [[livestock]] ranching, and commercial fishing (mainly for [[shellfish]]).<ref name=\"TDWR Sabine\"/>{{RP|III\u201320}}\n\n==Minor estuaries==\nTexas has five minor estuaries interspersed among its seven major estuary systems. These are smaller, less complicated estuaries with less significance to the state's hydrology, ecology, and economy. Several of these are simply the lower [[tidal reach]]es of particular rivers, without [[barrier islands]] or [[embayment]]s to separate them from the Gulf of Mexico.<ref>{{Cite web|title=Minor Estuaries of Texas|website=[[Texas Water Development Board]]|url=https://www.twdb.texas.gov/surfacewater/bays/minor_estuaries/index.asp|accessdate=March 11, 2020}}</ref>\n\n===Rio Grande Estuary===\nThe [[Rio Grande]] Estuary is located on the Texas\u2013Mexico border in Cameron County, south of Laguna Madre at the southern extremity of the Texas coast. It is a riverine estuary system consisting only of the lower reaches of the Rio Grande, with no associated bay.<ref>{{Cite web|title=Rio Grande Estuary|website=[[Texas Water Development Board]]|url=https://www.twdb.texas.gov/surfacewater/bays/minor_estuaries/rio_grande/index.asp|accessdate=March 11, 2020}}</ref>\n\n===East Matagorda Bay Estuary===\n{{Main|East Matagorda Bay}}\n[[East Matagorda Bay]] is a minor estuary located on the upper-mid Texas coast in Matagorda County immediately northeast of the Colorado\u2013Lavaca Estuary (Matagorda Bay). It has no significant river sources and is separated from the Gulf of Mexico by Matagorda Peninsula, only intermittently connecting with it through [[Brown Cedar Cut]]. The estuary has a surface area of {{Convert|37810|acre|ha}}, and its natural portions have an average depth of around {{Convert|3.4|ft|m|1}}<ref>{{Cite web|title=East Matagorda Bay|website=[[Texas Water Development Board]]|url=https://www.twdb.texas.gov/surfacewater/bays/minor_estuaries/east_matagorda/index.asp|accessdate=March 11, 2020}}</ref>\n\n===San Bernard River and Cedar Lakes Estuary===\nThe [[San Bernard River]] and [[Cedar Lakes (Texas)|Cedar Lakes]] Estuary is one of three minor estuaries located on the upper-mid Texas coast in Brazoria County between Matagorda Bay and Galveston Bay. It includes Cedar Lakes, [[Cowtrap Lake]], and the lower reaches of the San Bernard River, covering a surface area of {{Convert|3760|acre|ha}} with an average depth of {{Convert|2.1|ft|m|1}}.<ref>{{Cite web|title=San Bernard River and Cedar Lakes Estuary|website=[[Texas Water Development Board]]|url=https://www.twdb.texas.gov/surfacewater/bays/minor_estuaries/san_bernard/index.asp|accessdate=March 11, 2020}}</ref>\n\n===Brazos River Estuary===\nThe [[Brazos River]] Estuary is the second of three minor estuaries located on the upper-mid Texas coast in Brazoria County between Matagorda Bay and Galveston Bay. It is a riverine estuary system consisting only of the lower reaches of the Brazos River, with no associated bay.<ref>{{Cite web|title=Brazos River Estuary|website=[[Texas Water Development Board]]|url=https://www.twdb.texas.gov/surfacewater/bays/minor_estuaries/brazos/index.asp|accessdate=March 11, 2020}}</ref>\n\n===Christmas Bay Estuary===\n{{Main|Christmas Bay (Texas)}}\n[[Christmas Bay (Texas)|Christmas Bay]] is a minor estuary located on the upper-mid Texas coast in Brazoria County immediately southwest of the Trinity\u2013San Jacinto Estuary (Galveston Bay). It is fed by [[Bastrop Bayou]], separated from the Gulf of Mexico by [[Follet's Island]] and connecting with it through San Luis Pass and [[Cold Pass]]. Its minor extensions are [[Bastrop Bay]] to the north and [[Drum Bay]] to the southwest.<ref>{{Cite web|title=Christmas Bay|website=[[Texas Water Development Board]]|url=https://www.twdb.texas.gov/surfacewater/bays/minor_estuaries/christmas/index.asp|accessdate=March 11, 2020}}</ref> The estuary has a surface area of {{Convert|4173|acre|ha}}. Much of its shoreline is protected within the [[Brazoria National Wildlife Refuge]].<ref>{{Cite web|title=Texas GEMS \u2014 Christmas Bay Coastal Preserve|website=[[Texas Parks and Wildlife Department]]|url=https://tpwd.texas.gov/landwater/water/conservation/txgems/christma/index.phtml|accessdate=April 2, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{Commonscat-inline|Estuaries of Texas}}\n\n{{Estuaries of Texas}}\n\n[[Category:Estuaries of Texas| ]]\n", "name_user": "Bryanrutherford0", "label": "safe", "comment": "Wikilink", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Estuaries_of_Texas"}
